[## LECTURE 2.1 — AWS KMS: CUSTOMER-MANAGED KEYS AND KEY ROTATION]

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Encryption at rest protects your data when the underlying storage is compromised.
Whether that is a stolen hard drive, a misconfigured backup,
or an unauthorized snapshot.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
But here is what most people miss.
Encryption at rest is not just about turning on a setting.
It is about key management.
And that is where AWS KMS comes in.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Hi there, and welcome to Phase 2 of our SOC 2 journey.
In this phase, we are diving deep into cryptographic controls.
Specifically CC6.6 for encryption at rest and CC6.7 for encryption in transit.

4
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
By the end of these two hours, you will have implemented encryption
everywhere it matters, automated key rotation,
and built the evidence pipeline to prove it to any auditor.

5
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Let us start with encryption at rest.
AWS KMS, Key Management Service, is a FIPS 140-2 Level 3 validated service.
That is important because your auditor will ask
about the cryptographic standards you are using.

6
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
There are two types of keys you need to understand.
AWS-managed keys are created and managed by AWS.
They are fine for getting started.

7
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
But for SOC 2, you typically want customer-managed keys, or CMKs.
Why? Because you control the rotation policy.
You control who can use the key.
And you have audit logs of every key usage.

8
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
For our financial RAG agent, we are going to create separate KMS keys
for each service. One for RDS, one for S3, one for EBS.

9
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
This follows the principle of least privilege
and limits blast radius if a key is compromised.

10
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Let me show you the Terraform configuration
for KMS keys with customer management.

11
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
In terraform forward slash modules forward slash kms forward slash main dot tf.
Start with a data source for the IAM policy document.

12
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
First statement: Enable IAM User Permissions.
Effect Allow. Principal root account.
Actions kms colon asterisk. Resources asterisk.

13
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
This gives the root account full control so you never lock yourself out.

14
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Second statement: Allow RDS Service.
Effect Allow. Principal Service rds dot amazonaws dot com.

15
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Actions include kms colon Encrypt, kms colon Decrypt,
kms colon GenerateDataKey, and kms colon DescribeKey.

16
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Third statement: Allow Backup Service.
Effect Allow. Principal Service backup dot amazonaws dot com.

17
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Actions include kms colon Decrypt and kms colon GenerateDataKey.

18
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Fourth statement: Deny Deletion Without MFA.
Effect Deny. Principal asterisk.

19
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Actions include kms colon DeleteAlias and kms colon ScheduleKeyDeletion.
Condition BoolIfExists aws colon MultiFactorAuthPresent equals false.

20
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
This statement is critical for SOC 2.
It requires multi-factor authentication for any key deletion.

21
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Now create the key resources.

22
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
First, aws_kms_key for RDS.
Description colon CMK for RDS encryption dash dash CC6.6.
deletion_window_in_days colon thirty.
enable_key_rotation colon true.
policy set to the data source we created.

23
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Tags include Name colon financial-rag-rds,
Purpose colon rds-encryption,
Control colon CC6.6,
Environment colon var dot environment.

24
00:11:30,000 --> 00:12:00,000
Then create an aws_kms_alias for RDS.
name colon alias forward slash financial-rag-rds.
target_key_id set to aws_kms_key dot rds dot key_id.

25
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Repeat for S3. aws_kms_key dot s3.
Description colon CMK for S3 encryption dash dash CC6.6.
enable_key_rotation colon true.

26
00:12:30,000 --> 00:13:00,000
Alias colon alias forward slash financial-rag-s3.

27
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:30,000
Repeat for EBS. aws_kms_key dot ebs.
Description colon CMK for EBS encryption dash dash CC6.6.
enable_key_rotation colon true.

28
00:13:30,000 --> 00:14:00,000
Alias colon alias forward slash financial-rag-ebs.

29
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:30,000
Repeat for CloudWatch. aws_kms_key dot cloudwatch.
Description colon CMK for CloudWatch log encryption dash dash CC6.6.

30
00:14:30,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Output the key ARNs and IDs for use in other modules.

31
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:30,000
Now apply the Terraform configuration.
Change to the terraform directory. Run terraform init.
Then terraform apply with target equals module dot kms.

32
00:15:30,000 --> 00:16:00,000
After apply completes, verify key rotation is enabled.

33
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:30,000
Run a loop for each alias.
For alias in financial-rag-rds, financial-rag-s3, financial-rag-ebs.
Get the key ID using aws kms describe-key.

34
00:16:30,000 --> 00:17:00,000
Then aws kms get-key-rotation-status for that key ID.
Query KeyRotationEnabled.
The output should be true for every key.

35
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:30,000
Save this as evidence.
Create a directory in soc2-evidence with today's date under CC6.6.

36
00:17:30,000 --> 00:18:00,000
For each alias, run aws kms get-key-rotation-status
and output to kms-rotation-dash alias dot json.

37
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:30,000
Your lab exercise is to create the KMS keys using the Terraform configuration.
Then run the verification commands.
Confirm that enable_key_rotation equals true for all three keys.

38
00:18:30,000 --> 00:19:00,000
Save the rotation status outputs.
These become evidence for CC6.6.

39
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:30,000
In the next lecture, we will attach these KMS keys
to RDS, S3, and EBS.

