[## LECTURE 2.3 — S3 ENCRYPTION AT REST]

77
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
S3 encryption is simpler than RDS because it can be applied
to existing buckets without migration.
But the common mistake is enabling encryption without enforcing it.

78
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
If your bucket policy does not deny unencrypted uploads,
someone could upload an object without encryption headers.
That object would be stored in plaintext.

79
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Your auditor will ask: can you prove every object
in your S3 buckets is encrypted?
The answer must be yes.

80
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Let me show you the S3 encryption configuration with enforcement.

81
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
In terraform forward slash modules forward slash s3 forward slash main dot tf.
Create a locals block with a map of bucket names.

82
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Buckets include backups, embeddings, ingestion, and evidence.

83
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
First, create the buckets.
Use for_each over the local buckets map.

84
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
resource aws_s3_bucket dot buckets.
bucket set to each dot value.
Tags include Name, Environment, Control CC6.6.

85
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Second, configure server-side encryption.
resource aws_s3_bucket_server_side_encryption_configuration.

86
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
For each bucket, apply a rule with
apply_server_side_encryption_by_default.
sse_algorithm colon aws:kms.
kms_master_key_id set to var dot s3_kms_key_arn.

87
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
bucket_key_enabled set to true.
This reduces KMS request costs while maintaining security.

88
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Third, create a bucket policy that denies unencrypted uploads.

89
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
First statement. Sid colon DenyUnencryptedObjectUploads.
Effect Deny. Principal asterisk.
Action s3:PutObject.
Resource bucket ARN forward slash asterisk.

90
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Condition. Null colon s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption equals true.
This means: if the upload has no encryption header, deny it.

91
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
Second statement. Sid colon DenyNonKMSEncryption.
Effect Deny. Principal asterisk.
Action s3:PutObject.

92
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Condition. StringNotEquals colon
s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption equals aws:kms.
This means: if encryption is present but not KMS, deny it.

93
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Third statement. Sid colon DenyHTTP.
Effect Deny. Principal asterisk.
Action s3:asterisk.

94
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Condition. Bool colon aws:SecureTransport equals false.
This forces all S3 access over HTTPS.

95
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
Fourth, enable versioning.
resource aws_s3_bucket_versioning for each bucket.
status set to Enabled.

96
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Fifth, block public access.
resource aws_s3_bucket_public_access_block for each bucket.
Set all four block settings to true.

97
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Now apply the Terraform configuration.
terraform apply target equals module.s3.

98
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Verify S3 encryption.
Loop through each bucket name.

99
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Run aws s3api get-bucket-encryption for the bucket.
Query the SSEAlgorithm.
It should return aws:kms.

100
00:11:30,000 --> 00:12:00,000
Also query the KMSMasterKeyID.
It should match your customer-managed key ARN.

101
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Test that unencrypted uploads are rejected.
Run echo test pipe aws s3 cp dash to a test file.
Do not specify any encryption headers.

102
00:12:30,000 --> 00:13:00,000
The upload should fail with an AccessDenied error.
The bucket policy blocks it.

103
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:30,000
Save the evidence.
For each bucket, run get-bucket-encryption
and output to s3-encryption-dash bucket dot json.

104
00:13:30,000 --> 00:14:00,000
Your lab exercise is to apply the S3 encryption configuration.
Verify that all buckets have SSE-KMS enabled.

105
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:30,000
Test that an unencrypted upload is rejected.
Save the bucket encryption outputs as evidence.

106
00:14:30,000 --> 00:15:00,000
In the next lecture, we will configure EBS encryption for EKS nodes.

